m the Gaelic personal name <i>Boite</i>, of uncertain origin.","Scottish and Irish: from the Gaelic epithet <i>buidhe</i> ‘yellow(-haired)’. Compare   Bowie  .","Manx: from <b>Mac Gille Buidhe</b> ‘son of the yellow-haired lad’ (compare 2 above)."],"variants":[{"name":"Bowie","meanings":["Scottish: from Gaelic <i>buidhe</i> ‘yellow’, i.e. ‘yellow-haired’, pronounced as two syllables. The equivalent term in Ireland is <i>buí</i>, often Anglicized as <i>boy</i>. The surname may also be a shortened form of   Gilboy  .","Irish: Anglicized form of <b>Ó Buadhaigh</b> (see   Bogue  )."]},{"name":"Boyde","meanings":["Scottish (Glasgow): variant of   Boyd  ."]}]},{"name":"Ellen","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Helen  , although now no longer associated with that name. Initial <i>H-</i> tended to be added and dropped rather capriciously, leading to many doublets (  compare for example  Esther   and   Hester  ). It is also sometimes used as a short form of   Eleanor  , to which, however, it is unrelated."],"variants":[{"name":"Eleanor","meanings":["From an Old French respelling of the Old Provençal name <i>Alienor</i>. This has sometimes been taken as a derivative of   Helen  , but it is more probably of Germanic derivation (the first element being <i>ali</i> ‘other, foreign’ the second is obscure). The name was introduced to England by  Eleanor of Aquitaine  (  1122–1204 ), who came from Aquitaine in south-west France to be the wife of  King Henry II . It was also borne by Eleanor of Provence, the wife of  Henry III , and Eleanor of Castile, wife of  Edward I ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Ellen Boyd was born in 1370, in Scotland, United Kingdom. She had at least 2 sons with Hugh Barclay 5th of Kilbirnie."},"et":{"1370–Deceased":"1370–Surnud","1375–1430":"1375–1430","1390–1456":"1390–1456","1410–1456":"1410–1456","1370–Female":"1370–Surnud","1456":"1456","1410":"1410","